\begin_layout Standard
Since we can only measure the radiation from star-forming regions astronomers
 use polarimetry to infer properties like the direction and magnitude of
 the magnetic field.
 The Davis-Chandrasekhar-Fermi (DCF) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chandrasekhar1953"

\end_inset

 is one method that uses the dispersion of polarization angles (PA) of linear
 polarization (LP) to find the magnitude and direction of the plane-of-the-sky
 component of the magnetic field.
 The presence of a magnetic field leads to linearly polarized radiation
 because dust molecules will align themselves to the field.
 The aligned particles emit radiation that is linearly polarized.
 Aligned dust will also absorb radiation whose polarization is aligned with
 its long axis, acting as a sort of polarizing grid.
 Thus measuring the amount of linear polarization in the infrared continuum
 tells us about the degree to which the dust is aligned with the magnetic
 field which in turn tells us about the strength of the magnetic field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chandrasekhar1953,Crutcher2012"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The alignment of molecules and their interaction with the ambient magnetic
 field can cause that molecule's transitions to be linearly polarized by
 a few percent through the Goldreich-Kylafis effect 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Goldreich1981"

\end_inset

.
 As with dust, the PA associated with the linear polarization in the spectral
 line can be measured and used to infer properties of the magnetic field
 through a dispersion analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Chandrasekhar1953,Crutcher2012"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A significant amount of unexpected circular polarization was reported by
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Houde2013"

\end_inset

 in a rotational transition of CO using the Caltech Submillimeter Observatory
 (CSO), a common tracer of the magnetic field 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Crutcher2012"

\end_inset

.
 The presence of circular polarization in a molecular transition can be
 explained with Zeeman splitting for some molecules/transitions possessing
 a significant magnetic momeny (e.g., CN), but CO is highly insensitive to
 the Zeeman effect.
 In addition, the observed Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 profile in Orion KL was positive and symmetric, which is also unexpected
 since Zeeman splitting usually gives rise to an antisymmetric Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 profile.
 To explain this detection a model was proposed whereby linearly polarized
 light is converted to circularly polarized light through anisotropic resonant
 scattering (ARS) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Houde2013,Houde2014"

\end_inset

.
 This was further tested in IC443 by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hezareh2013"

\end_inset

 where the measured circularly polarized flux of CO lines (
\begin_inset Formula $J=2\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

) and (
\begin_inset Formula $J=1\rightarrow0$
\end_inset

) were `re-added' into the measured linearly polarized flux to correct the
 polarization angles.
 They found that the polarization angles obtained from the CO tracers only
 agreed with those obtained from dust polarimetry after the circularly polarized
 flux was accounted for.
 If ARS is common to other objects then using linear polarization in CO
 as a tracer of the magnetic field will have a systematic error unless the
 circular polarization of CO's lines are also measured.
 The goal of this paper is to show several examples of such circular polarizatio
n.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Measurement of Circular Polarization with Radio Interferometry
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Measurement-with-Radio"

\end_inset

The measurement of circular polarization is challenging to calibrate, especially
 when using radio interferometers like the SMA or ALMA.
 The SMA polarimeter uses a quarter-waveplate (QWP) to convert incident
 linearly polarized light to circularly polarized light primarily to measure
 linear polarization.
 While not its intended use, the QWP can work the other way to measure CP:
 incident CP is converted to LP and then measured by the receivers.
 ALMA on the other hand uses linear feeds and measures the linearly polarized
 light directly.
 While both types of feeds can be used to measure circular polarization,
 the calibration process is different 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Sault1996"

\end_inset

.
 Currently ALMA does not support measuring Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 reliably.
 The SMA has been used to take precise measurements of CP in Sgr A* as reported
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Munoz2012"

\end_inset

.
 For a discussion on measuring CP with radio interferometry and on design
 choices at the SMA (such as the choice of converting from linear- to circular-p
olarization and vice-versa) see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hamaker1996,Marrone2008"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Linear vs.
 Circular Feeds
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To illustrate briefly the differences between the two feed types consider
 the following: with orthogonal circular polarization bases, the Stokes
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 parameter for a beam of light is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $V=\langle E_{L}^{2}\rangle-\langle E_{R}^{2}\rangle$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 is the electric field vector and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 correspond to the orthogonal left-CP and right-CP bases.
 With orthogonal linear bases Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $V=-2\text{Im}(E_{x}E_{y}^{*})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 are the linear bases.
 In the circular case we take the difference of two measured intensities
 while the linear feed case requires us to measure the phase of the electromagne
tic wave.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now when the measurement is made with interferometry it is the visibilities
 –the correlated waveforms between a pair of antennae– that are measured.
 In the circular case the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 visibility is roughly 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{V}_{\text{V}}\propto\text{\mathcal{V}}_{RR}-\text{\mathcal{V}}_{LL}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\mathcal{V}}_{RR}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\mathcal{V}}_{LL}$
\end_inset

 are the visibilities obtained from correlating two antenna measuring right-CP
 and left-CP respectively.
 In the linear feed case the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 visibility is coupled with the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 visibilities 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "see Section 4.1 of"
key "Thompson2001"

\end_inset

.
 This means the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 of any calibration object must be measured as well.
 This is not possible with the SMA setup.
\end_layout

