\end_inset

.
 We repeat here the arguments made in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Observations"

\end_inset

 that these detections are real.
 We then discuss earlier detections of CP and summarize how ARS can explain
 the detections presented in this work.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Firstly we take the average of all the visibility data and note that the
 peak Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is not proportional to the peak Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 at any particular frequency –a large Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 at 347.25GHz for example does not indicate a corresponding peak in Stokes
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 This property indicates that there isn't significant leakage of Stokes
 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 into Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 This is true in Orion KL (where CO and SiO are the strongest lines).
 This also seems to be true in the visibilities of IRC+10216: the CS and
 SiS lines have similar strengths but the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 at SiS is twice as intense.
 However in the same object H
\begin_inset Formula $^{13}$
\end_inset

CN and CO have Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 intensities that appear proportional to their Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 intensity (stronger 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 means stronger 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also note that the shapes of the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 signals vary across the frequency band and interpret this to mean that
 the signals are not instrumental in nature.
 For example Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SiO"

\end_inset

 shows a spectrum from Orion KL with Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 in CO and SiO.
 The SiO signal is purely negative (indicating only left-circular polarization)
 but the CO signal is antisymmetric and is initially positive and then becomes
 negative, indicating the presence of both LCP and RCP.
 This has a physical explanation using ARS in terms of blue-shifted and
 red-shifted scattering populations that will be considered later.
 We know of no instrumental mechanism for producing such a signature.
 This argument only applies to Orion KL.
 In the other objects the Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 signal is always positive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally we checked and confirmed that there were no Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 signals in the continuum larger than those found at molecular lines like
 CO and SiO.
 Finding a large signal in the continuum could indicate the data is suffering
 from instrumental artifacts since we only expect conversion of linear to
 circular polarization at the frequencies of molecular transitions.
 This is not the case: we only find Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 peaks at frequencies that correspond with emission from molecular lines
 and there is no significant CP in the continuum.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For these reasons we believe the CP reported here while quite probably contamina
ted with instrumental effects are real and originate from each of these
 objects.
 It is thus important to develop the instrumentation and improve the measurement
 and calibration of CP for future studies of magnetic fields using polarimetry.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Earlier Detections
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Circular polarization in a spectral line of a Zeeman insensitive molecule
 was first reported in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Houde2013"

\end_inset

 where roughly 2% CP was detected in the 
\begin_inset Formula $^{12}$
\end_inset

CO 
\begin_inset Formula $(J=2\rightarrow1)$
\end_inset

 line at 230.5 GHz in Orion KL using the CSO.
 The CP signal was positive and symmetric (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-shaped).
 The observation was repeated three months after the first measurement to
 confirm the result wasn't spurious, with similar results.
 Additionally the strong line of HCN 
\begin_inset Formula $(J=3\rightarrow2)$
\end_inset

 at 265.9 GHz in Orion KL was measured and no CP higher than the 0.1% level
 was detected.
 The detection in CO and the absence of a detection in HCN indicates that
 the CSO observations were not suffering from leakage into Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 and highlights the CO molecule as a source of non-Zeeman CP.
 In all the objects presented here we find CP in 
\begin_inset Formula $^{12}$
\end_inset

CO 
\begin_inset Formula $(J=3\rightarrow2)$
\end_inset

 at 345.8 GHz (except for in NGC1333 where the CO line is weak).
 This is consistent with the original 2013 detection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In follow up work 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Hezareh2013"

\end_inset

 examined the supernova remnant IC 443 using dust polarimetry with PolKa
 at APEX and polarization maps of 
\begin_inset Formula $^{12}$
\end_inset

CO 
\begin_inset Formula $(J=2\rightarrow1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(J=1\rightarrow0)$
\end_inset

 taken with the IRAM 30m telescope.
 They found that initially the linear polarization maps of dust and CO differed
 greatly in their polarization angles.
 Expecting that there was conversion of linear to circular polarization
 due to ARS, the CO Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 flux was then reinserted into the CO Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 flux.
 The resulting CO map's polarization angles now agreed very well with the
 polarization angles in the dust map 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
before "Fig. 9 of"
key "Hezareh2013"

\end_inset

.
 This result gives strong support for a conversion from linear to circular
 polarization.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Anisotropic Resonant Scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Anisotropic resonant scattering was the mechanism first proposed by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Houde2013"

\end_inset

 to explain the presence of CP in the transitions of CO, but failed to explain
 the observed positive and symmetric 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-shaped Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 profile.
 In a follow up paper 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Houde2014"

\end_inset

 considered observations of Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 in SiO masers and showed that different profile shapes easily arose if
 there were populations of scattering foreground molecules slightly outside
 of the velocity range of the line.
 For example in that case a blue-shifted scattering population of molecules
 results in a negative 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cup$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-shaped profile and a red-shifted population results in a positive 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\cap$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-shaped profile.
 The presence of both a blue- and red-shifted population results in an antisymme
tric 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

S
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

-shaped profile like the one seen in the top left panel of Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:results"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The basic principle of ARS can be illustrated by considering linearly polarized
 radiation oriented at some angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 to the foreground magnetic field.
 The incident and scattered radiation can be written in terms of the 
\emph on
n
\emph default
-photon states as 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Houde2013"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
|\psi\rangle= & \alpha|n_{||}\rangle+\beta|n_{\perp}\rangle\\
|\psi'\rangle\simeq & \alpha e^{i\phi}|n_{||}\rangle+\beta|n_{\perp}\rangle
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\cos(\theta)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\sin(\theta)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 is a phase shift incurred after multiple scattering events.
 Following the definitions of the Stokes parameters and using the appropriate
 bases the Stokes parameters for the scattered radiation can be found to
 be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{array}{cc}
I= & \alpha^{2}+\beta^{2}\\
Q= & \alpha^{2}-\beta^{2}\\
U= & 2\alpha\beta\cos(\phi)\\
V= & 2\alpha\beta\sin(\phi)
\end{array}
\]

\end_inset

This implies that Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 is lost to Stokes 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

.
 A calculation of the form of 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 can be found in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Houde2013"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

